{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778291082,"nonce":"ckEd5kd09DqlCJLFbLR00dXLM7c=","title":"Hyperparameter sweep on analytical Riccati: cost-function exponent + horizon length effects on delta-v","message":"User-proposed analysis from the 2×2×2 baseline matrix session.\n\n## Motivation\n\nThe C\u0026S Eq. 15 cost schedule uses a (t/N)^6 terminal-cliff exponent (α=6) with a fixed horizon N. The current empirical cost-schedule sweep issue (`6ec6b19`) sweeps α on a fixed horizon but is framed around trained models. This issue focuses on the **analytical Riccati** side: how does the adversary's Δv advantage vary as functions of both α and horizon N, using the existing Riccati infrastructure?\n\n## Questions\n\n1. How does Δv vary as α ∈ {2, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 10}?\n2. How does Δv vary as n_steps ∈ {40, 60, 80, 120, 200}?\n3. Is there an (α, n_steps) combination that maximises Δv subject to the task remaining a plausible reaching task?\n4. Could a constrained hyperparameter optimisation find this frontier automatically?\n\n## Implementation\n\nExtend the existing `cs_eq15_cost_schedule(...)` builder to accept `alpha` as a kwarg (currently hardcoded to 6). Use the existing Riccati infrastructure with the 8-state + delay augmentation. Run a grid over (α, n_steps) and plot Δv as a heatmap.\n\nThis is useful both as analytical understanding of the adversary's sensitivity landscape AND as input to the empirical cost-schedule sweep `6ec6b19` (which will need to know which α values are worth testing on trained networks).\n\n## Cross-refs\n\n- Empirical sweep (existing, framed around trained models): `6ec6b19`\n- Related adversary flavor-of-max tracking: `c99ad9d`\n- Smoothness retrain context that prompted this: `efc4d68`","files":null}]}